snippet.textDisplay:
💕 Story of Sohni and Mahiwal

Long ago, in the region of Punjab, there lived a beautiful girl named Sohni, the daughter of a potter. She was very talented and painted beautiful floral designs on the clay pots her father made. Her pots were famous all around the area.

One day, a young trader named Izzat Baig (a merchant from Bukhara, Central Asia) came to her village. When he saw Sohni, he instantly fell in love with her. He started visiting her shop every day, buying pots just to see her. Soon, Sohni also fell in love with him.

However, when her family found out about this, they were angry and forced Sohni to marry another man, a man from her own community. Izzat Baig, heartbroken, gave up his business and started living as a poor cattle herder near Sohni’s village. People began calling him “Mahiwal”, which means herdsman.

Every night, Sohni would secretly swim across the Chenab River to meet Mahiwal. She used an earthen pot (ghara) to help her float on the water.

One stormy night, her sister-in-law discovered her secret meetings and replaced her baked clay pot with an unbaked one. When Sohni entered the river that night, the pot melted in the strong current, and she drowned. Mahiwal, seeing her struggle, jumped into the river to save her — but both died together in the water.

Their love story became a symbol of eternal love and devotion, remembered in songs, poetry, and folklore across Punjab and Sindh.
